  "title": "ECG: hypokalaemia",
  "body_html": "<div>ECG features of hypokalaemia<br /><ul><li>U waves</li><li>small or absent T waves (occasionally inversion)</li><li>prolong PR interval</li><li>ST depression</li><li>long QT</li></ul><br />The ECG below shows typical U waves. Note also the borderline PR interval.<br /><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011b.jpg'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011.jpg'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>&copy; Image used on license from </span><a href='http://hqmeded-ecg.blogspot.com/'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Dr Smith, University of Minnesota</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011b.jpg'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a><a  border='0' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011c.jpg'  \n\t\ttarget='_blank' ><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass2.png'/></a></td></tr></table></div><br />One registered user suggests the following rhyme<br /><ul><li>In Hypokalaemia, U have no Pot and no T, but a long PR and a long QT</li></ul></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodylinks\"></div>\n\n<div id=\"mybodymedia\"></div>\n\n\n<div id=\"categorynum\">2</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategorynum\">2</div>\n\n<div id=\"categoryname\">Physiology</div>\n\n<div id=\"subcategoryname\">Cardiovascular physiology</div>\n<div id=\"mybody\">\n\n<div id=\"body_content\">\nECG features of hypokalaemia<br /><ul><li>U waves</li><li>small or absent T waves (occasionally inversion)</li><li>prolong PR interval</li><li>ST depression</li><li>long QT</li></ul><br />The ECG below shows typical U waves. Note also the borderline PR interval.<br /><br /><div class=\"text-center\"><table><tr><td align = 'left' colspan='2'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011b.jpg'><img class='ajaximage' src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011.jpg'/></a></td></tr><tr><td valign='top' align='left'> <span style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;'>&copy; Image used on license from </span><a href='http://hqmeded-ecg.blogspot.com/'  target='_blank' style = 'font-size:11px; color:LightGray;' >Dr Smith, University of Minnesota</a></td><td align='right'><a data-fancybox class='fancybox lbmagglasslink' rel='group' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011b.jpg'><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass.png'/></a><a  border='0' href='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/images_MRCEMnotes/ecg011c.jpg'  \n\t\ttarget='_blank' ><img src='https://d20g8jnrcgqmxh.cloudfront.net/css/images/mag_glass2.png'/></a></td></tr></table></div><br />One registered user suggests the following rhyme<br /><ul><li>In Hypokalaemia, U have no Pot and no T, but a long PR and a long QT</li></ul></div>\n\n\n<BR><BR><br><br></div>",
